SIMPLE: relieve
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Relieve
<hw>Re*lieve"</hw> <pr>(r?-l?v")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Relieved</conjf>
<pr>(-l?vd")</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Relieving</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>releven</ets>, F.
<ets>relever</ets> to raise again, discharge, relieve, fr. L.
<ets>relevare</ets> to lift up, raise, make light, relieve; pref.
<ets>re-</ets> re- + <ets>levare</ets> to raise, fr. <ets>levis</ets>
light. See <er>Levity</er>, and cf. <er>Relevant</er>,
<er>Relief</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To lift up; to raise again, as
one who has fallen; to cause to rise.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Piers Plowman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cause to seem to rise; to put in relief; to give
prominence or conspicuousness to; to set off by contrast.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Her tall figure <qex>relieved</qex> against the blue sky; seemed
almost of supernatural height.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To raise up something in; to introduce a contrast or
variety into; to remove the monotony or sameness of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The poet must . . . sometimes <qex>relieve</qex> the subject with
a moral reflection.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To raise or remove, as anything which depresses,
weighs down, or crushes; to render less burdensome or afflicting; to
alleviate; to abate; to mitigate; to lessen; <as>as, to <ex>relieve</ex>
pain; to <ex>relieve</ex> the wants of the poor.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To free, wholly or partly, from any burden, trial,
evil, distress, or the like; to give ease, comfort, or consolation to;
to give aid, help, or succor to; to support, strengthen, or deliver;
<as>as, to <ex>relieve</ex> a besieged town</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now lend assistance and <qex>relieve</qex> the poor.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To release from a post, station, or duty; to put
another in place of, or to take the place of, in the bearing of any
burden, or discharge of any duty.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who hath <qex>relieved</qex> you?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To ease of any imposition, burden, wrong, or
oppression, by judicial or legislative interposition, as by the removal
of a grievance, by indemnification for losses, or the like; to
right.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To alleviate; assuage; succor; assist; aid; help;
support; substain; ease; mitigate; lighten; diminish; remove; free;
remedy; redress; indemnify.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Relievement</ent>⟦br⟧
